        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-13T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-13T19:00:00-05:00" n="312" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d312">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.248/1–1345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-13T20:00:00-04:00">January 13, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. The War Department desires to obtain the permission of the Portuguese
                    Government to make landings in Lisbon of planes of the Air Transport Command on
                    regularly scheduled flights from the United States to Paris and Rome. As Mr.
                        George<note n="1" xml:id="d312fn1">William Perry George, Assistant Chief of
                        the Division of Western European Affairs.</note> is thoroughly familiar with
                    this project he is being sent to Lisbon, accompanied by Colonel Payne,<note n="2" xml:id="d312fn2">Lt. Col. Robert G. Payne of the Air Transport
                        Command.</note> to assist you. They expect to leave Washington the morning
                    of the 16th by transport plane and to proceed via Casablanca.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
